<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Sat, 22 Apr 2006 17:41:16 -0400
From: Maria Compte <compte@dooleyintermed.org>
Source: La Nacion, Buenos Aires. Argentina [Translated by submitter] [edited]
<http://buscador.lanacion.com.ar/Nota.asp?nota_id=799692&high=caballos>

Sanitary Alert: Dangerous Virus Enters the Country
----------------
For the 1st time, at least 2 cases of the serious West Nile Virus, a
disease propagated among birds and other animals through the bite of
a mosquito, have been detected in Argentina. This was confirmed last
night to La Nacion by a knowledgeable source from the National
Service for Agricultural Sanitation and Quality (Senasa). Both cases
were detected in horses, which typically are one of the mammal
species affected by this virus.
The same information source added that yesterday and in accordance to
international regulations, Senasa reported the news to the
International Office for Epizootics, based in Paris; it also informed
that it has temporarily banned the export of horses beginning next
Monday [24 Apr 2006].
As of today Senasa has not offered any specific details, like the
exact number of animals affected, the name of the breeding ranch, its
geographic location, the viral strain, or the preventive strategies
to be taken, all questions that are going to be addressed early next
week, as per our source.
Unofficially, though, there have been speculations that the equines
affected are Pure Bred racehorses from a ranch located in the county
of Capitan Sarmiento, in Buenos Aires Province, about 145 km. from
the capital city of Buenos Aires.
Doctor Horacio Lopez, Chief of Infectious Diseases of the School of
Medicine at the University of Buenos Aires, explained that most of
the infections in humans - about 80 percent-- do not produce any type
of symptoms. About 20 percent of infected people might show mild
flu-like symptoms.. And about one in 150 infected patients might
develop a more serious disease (encephalitis, meningitis or
meningoencephalitis).
Dr. Lopez mentioned that WNV belongs to the flavivirus family
"along with Saint Louis Virus [SLE, St. Louis Encephalitis], which
was the cause of the encephalitis outbreak in Cordoba Province last
year. Other related viruses are dengue and yellow fever."
From the Ministry of Health, Dr. Andres Leibovich, Undersecretary
for Preventive and Health Promotion Programs, informed that his
agency still does not have any information regarding the cases.
"Nevertheless, we are already taking measures and along with Senasa
and the Epidemiology Section of the Ministry of Health of Buenos
Aires Province we have started to draft a preventive strategy. But we
need to act with the responsibility that this subject deserves; our
epidemiological surveillance system has worked very well until now,
and we don't want to set off the alert in the population until we
have all the information that we need in this case."
Dr. Tomas Orduna, Chief of the Regional Pathologies and Tropical
Medicine at Muniz Hospital (an Infectious Diseases Reference Hospital
in Argentina), said that "it is very unusual that the cases detected
have occurred in mammals, not in birds; horses are one of the
sentinel species, but it is birds the ones that are the main
reservoir of the virus."
Dr. Orduna expanded saying that "if the virus is already in
mosquitoes, I must deduct from this that there have to be birds
infected as well, but that they have not been detected as yet.
Presently we are having the South-to-North bird migration (it is the
beginning of the winter season in the Southern Hemisphere), and the
epidemiological logic tells us that the virus will get here from the
Northern Hemisphere during their North-to-South migration. It is very
important to be cautious about the possibility of false positive diagnoses."
--
