From: Maria Compte <compte@dooleyintermed.org>
Date: Sun, 23 Apr 2006 15:52:10 -0400
Source: La Nacion Online, Buenos Aires, Argentina [Trans. by
submitter] [edited]
<http://buscador.lanacion.com.ar/Nota.asp?nota_id=799924&high=caballos>
Comment from Maria Compte:
This is a follow up to the piece contributed yesterday on the
(possible) detection of West Nile virus in Argentina for the 1st time
[see [1] above]. The area around of San Antonio de Areco is well
known for high quality racing and polo horse-breeding ranches. In
addition, I am including a short article from March 2006 on mass
mortality in aquatic birds in Mendoza Province, which may or may not
be due to the same pathogen (Mendoza is located near Chile, more than
1000 km west of Buenos Aires Province location where the infected
racing horses have been detected).
Death of 2 Horses due to West Nile Virus is Confirmed
-------------------
They belong to a Racehorse Breeding Ranch in San Antonio de Areco. No
cases have been detected in humans, but a prevention plan is being set in place
The Ministry of Health of Buenos Aires Province confirmed yesterday
the death of 2 horses affected by West Nile virus (WNV) at the same
time that announced that no human cases have been reported, and that
it is already working in a preventive campaign.
The cases, which La Nacion informed of in yesterday's edition, were
communicated to the provincial government by the National Service for
Agricultural Sanitation and Quality (Senasa), last Thursday [20 Apr
2006]. On Friday [21 Apr 2006] a meeting between representatives of
that agency and of the national and provincial Ministries of Health took place.
"During this meeting we analyzed what actions to take, which must be
based on prevention. It must be emphasized to the population that
there are no human cases to date, and that this virus is not
contagious from person to person" told La Nacion the Director of
Epidemiology of Buenos Aires Province, Maria del Carmen Weis. "People
that might have been in contact with the affected horses should not
worry either. A human being can only be infected by the bite of an
infected common mosquito. it is in this aspect of the disease where
prevention must be developed", added the specialist. Still, since
1999 in the United States about 14 000 cases of people infected have
been detected, of whom more than 500 died.
The horses that died here as a consequence of WNV were 2 Pure Bred
Racing animals from San Antonio de Areco (Note: location is 113 km
northwest of city of Buenos Aires). The County's Mayor, Eduardo
Jordan, told La Nacion: "We are working to inform the population and
avoid misunderstanding and alarm. I don't yet know to which specific
farm the dead animals belong, we will know this on Monday (for
tomorrow)." It has been rumors that the affected ranch is an
important establishment that won several prestigious prices in the
last years, including the Carlos Pellegrini Grand Prize (Note: the
highest horse racetrack prize in Argentina)
Dr. Weis added that "Senasa is currently doing animal investigations,
and from the (human) sanitary areas we are working on prevention. We
are on alert and in continuing communication and epidemiological
surveillance." In the case that a person would be affected by WNV,
the consequences would depend on the virulence of the strain and the
immunological defenses of the patient. "There is no vaccine, and it
is a virus, so the treatment is based on observation of the
(clinical) evolution of the disease."
The confirmation of the arrival of the virus in the country has
brought worry to the horse breeding industry, based on the experience
of what happened in the United States in 2002, when the disease
sickened more than 15 000 horses, with a 30 percent mortality and
millions of dollars in losses for the horseracing industry.
Yesterday there where even speculations that one of the infected
horses died at the San Isidro Racetrack stables (One of the 2 main
racetracks in the city of Buenos Aires, located in a northern
suburb), after traveling from Entre Rios Province (about 400 km
northeast of Buenos Aires), but the President of the Racetrack
Committee of the Argentine Jockey Club, Pablo Piffaretti,
emphatically denied such version of the events. "To date [22 Apr
2006] at 2 PM, we have not have registered one single case. We know
that in the US horses are exposed to this disease and that it is
treated (?) with a vaccine. What I don't understand here is that a
horse has been the 1st to fall ill with the disease, when usually it
is birds the ones that are first detected. Monday [24 Apr 2006] we
will contact Senasa to work with them on this situation", said Piffaretti.
In addition, Mario Lopez Oliva, President of the Argentine
Association of Equine Veterinary Medicine, reminded that "Equines are
final hosts and do not transmit the disease to humans. The arrival of
this virus was only a matter of time and fortunately is findings us
well prepared, because we have good information on this disease. If
it would have first affected regular countryside horses, we most
people would probably not have noticed it." As per the expert's
opinion, it would not be necessary to cancel horse races, "unless all
the horses fell ill", and said that there are 2 types of vaccines
available for horses, one American and the other European, both of
which produce good immunity. Argentina is a strong exporter of sports
horses, an activity that has been temporarily suspended depending on
the sanitary regulations that will have to be put in place before the
horses are allowed to enter other regions. Just considering racing
animals, since 2005 over 500 horses were exported to other countries,
an trade that now will be put on hold.
--
Maria Emilia Compte, MD, MPH&TM
