[3]
Date: 23 Apr 2006
From: Maria Compte <compte@dooleyintermed.org>
Source:El Dia Newspaper (Online edition). La Plata, Buenos Aires
Province, [12 Mar 2006] [Trans. by submitter]

Concern in Mendoza for Discovery of Dead Birds
In a lagoon, more than 50 were found. Samples of the dead birds were
sent to the University of Buenos Aires. Avian flu is ruled out.
-------------------
Staff from the Undesecretariat for the Environment established a
state of alert in the Llancanelo Lagoon, Department of Malargue, as a
consequence of the death of over 50 birds, registered this summer.
Authorities sent samples to the University of Buenos Aires to be
studied, which turned out negative for avian influenza, but now we
are waiting to rule out hepatitis or West Nile virus", a disease that
already has entered South America and that is said that it could
arrive in Mendoza within 2 years.
The affected birds belong to the species known as Coscoroba
(Coscoroba coscoroba, a waterfowl that look like a cross between a
swan and a goose and are most closely related to whistling ducks;
these birds are mostly residents and breed in Argentina and Chile,
but some migration takes place before the Argentine winter season to
Paraguay and Southern/ Central Brazil). This is one of 130 species
that inhabit the Malargue bodies of water, some of them residents,
other migratory, and many of them with endangered species status.
Due to this reason, the alert was declared early in order to try to
stop the spread of the virus in the lakes and lagoon of the province,
considering the migratory routes and the fact that Llancanelo Lagoon
is a Southern breeding site for many bird species from the
hemisphere. The official plan is to minimize the risk of an
ecological disaster in that natural environment due to some avian
epidemic" as was indicated by a report released by the Department of
Fauna of the Undersecretariat for the Environment.
"We need to realize the real probability of the imminence of the
arrival of West Nile virus to Llancanelo", warned the report, about
the disease which attacks humans, birds, mosquitoes, horses, and other mammals.
In the meantime, an Program of Epidemic Surveillance and Emerging
Diseases has been set in motion, with the formation of a committee
that will coordinate and centralize the information and establish a
management strategy to follow. Also a protocol has been set up in
Malargue to analyze dead birds in Llancanelo and obtain results in
the shortest time possible. Studies requiring higher level of
complexity will be sent to Buenos Aires.
--
