Date: 23 Apr 2006
From: Carlos Hermida <hermida@fibertel.com.ar>
Subject: west nile virus

In spite of lack of official formalities news distributed by
[reputable] media indicate that an outbreak of West Nile Virus was
diagnosed in horses in Argentina.
This onset in deep autumn raise suspicion about previous undetected
virus circulation.
--
Carlos Hermida
<hermida@fibertel.com.ar>
[If these are the 1st documented cases in horses, there is likely no
natural immunity in the horses. That being the case, the disease if
often fatal in horses. Vaccination of horses is recommended. There
are 2 companies with vaccines available for horses in the US. There
may be other vaccines available in other countries. - Mod.TG]
[This is the 1st report of disease due to West Nile virus (WNV) in
South America. ProMED mail's prior report on the most southerly
extension of the virus in the Western Hemisphere was in Trinidad (see
ProMED-mail posting West Nile virus update 2005 - Western Hemisphere
(01) 20050106.0033) with a report of 2 seropositive horses and 3
seropositive birds. One wonders if the other countries along the
route (see map of South America at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/south_america_ref04.jpg>)
have had WNV infections but have not as yet confirmed the presence of
the virus in their countries (this moderator's favorite adage "seek
and ye shall find"). Information from knowledgeable sources in
Argentina, and in other countries in South America on WNV activity in
their countries would be very much appreciated.
While WNV has not commonly been reported from waterfowl, there has
been a wide range of species that have been infected with the virus
as seen in the North American experience. It is interesting that the
above newswire in [3] did speculate WNV as a possible etiology for
the avian die-off, mentioning that it has already entered South
America. For an excellent review of the North American experience
with WNV, see Glaser A. West Nile virus and North America: an
unfolding story. Rev. sci. tech. Off. int. Epiz., 2004, 23 (2),
557-568. available at:
<http://www.oie.int/eng/publicat/rt/2302/PDF/557-568glaser.pdf>.
For a map of Argentina see
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/argentina_pol96.jpg> - Mod. MPP
